                                     @{b}Usage@{ub}

Choose a topic:

    @{"  How To Snap Windows  " link HowToSnap}
    @{" How To Unsnap Windows " link HowToUnsnap}

    @{"  Snapper Preferences  " link Preferences}

@endnode

@node HowToSnap "Snapping windows with Snapper"
                        @{b}How To Snap Windows With Snapper@{ub}

@{fg shine}1.@{fg text} Click in the window you want to snapshot. Make sure it's title will always be
   the same upon opening. If it isn't, then the window cannot be snapshotted.

@{fg shine}2.@{fg text} Hit the assigned hotkey SNAPKEY (defaults to control lshift [)

@{fg shine}3.@{fg text} Your window has been snapped! The next time you open it, the window will
   appear in the position and size it is currently in.

@endnode

@node HowToUnsnap "Unsnapping windows with Snapper"
                       @{b}How To Unsnap Windows With Snapper@{ub}

@{fg shine}1.@{fg text} Click in the window you want to unsnapshot.

@{fg shine}2.@{fg text} Hit the assigned hotkey UNSNAPKEY (defaults to control lshift ])

@{fg shine}3.@{fg text} Your window has been unsnapped! The next time you open it, the window will be
   free to open anywhere on the screen.

@endnode

@node Tooltypes "Snapper Tooltypes..."
                                   @{b}Tooltypes@{ub}

Snapper recognises the following tooltypes:

@{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub}

Commodities priority.

@{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}

Key combination used to pop up the @{" preferences " link Preferences} window.

@{b}SNAPKEY@{ub}

Key combination used to snapshot a window.

@{b}UNSNAPKEY@{ub}

Key combination used to unsnapshot a window.

@endnode

@node Preferences "Snapper Preferences..."
                              @{b}Snapper Preferences@{ub}

The Snapper preferences window lets you add/remove any windows which have been
snapped, and to manually change their positions and dimensions (although this is
not recommended). It is fairly intuitive, so I won't bother explaining the
basics. You can bring up the window with the assigned CX_POPKEY (defaults to
control lshift s).

The Update button allows you to rescan the snapped window list and to update
the preferences list of windows. This is needed because Snapper does not keep
updating the preferences window every time another window is snapped.

Your changes will only take effect when you click Save.

@endnode

@node Bugs "Bug Reports..."
                                  @{b}Bug Reports@{ub}

If you discover a bug whilst using Snapper, please report it to me as soon as
possible. If you want to report a bug, try to include with your report (if you
think it's necessary):

    * Your system setup (hardware/software running at time)

    * Circumstances leading to the problem

    * A detailed description of the problem itself (Software Failure numbers,
      erratic behaviour, etc.)

    * Circumstances after the problem (system stability, locked up, bad encoded
      files, etc.)

Since I'm not on the Internet with my Amiga, I'd appreciate bug reports if
either the email or newsgroup systems don't work. I think they're working OK,
but I can't check easily.

Mail all bug reports to me at: tone_20@my-Deja.com.

@endnode

@node About "A few technical notes on Snapper"
                                 @{b}About Snapper@{ub}

Snapper has been fully tested with Enforcer and Mungwall, and has been checked
for memory leaks.

Snapper was developed using:

                * Storm C Compiler --> Wahay! I got Storm C at last.

                * GoldEd           --> The BEST text editor ever written.

                * Enforcer         --> The original and the best.

                * Mungwall         --> Still works gr8 for me.

                * Sushi            --> Damn useful.

I've included source code for all you prospecting coders out there to play with.
I believe that with the Amiga in it's current state, it is necessary to
encourage more programmers by giving them example source. In this way, I hope
that other people can learn from what I myself have learned, much of which came
from studying other people's source. I hope that, if you are a programmer, you
will consider doing this as well.

The source can be compiled straight into Storm C (using the supplied project
file), although the file paths may need changing. With a little modification,
the source should also work on other compilers. The code is all yours to play
with, have fun!

@endnode

